Speaker 1: I talked a little earlier about returning a prescription because I didn't finish the—

Speaker 2: whole order and they didn't send what they said they were going to send, then they put—

Speaker 1: me on a recurring refill, and I got a second one I never even ordered, and then she had—

Speaker 2: me look at the pill and said, well, they sent you the wrong one anyway, and so that's why—

Speaker 1: I probably didn't finish off the order, I decided to cancel, and then she hung up on—

Speaker 2: me.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: And what information are you looking for, Nick?

Speaker 1: Are you just looking to see how to return it, or what do we need?

Speaker 1: with.

Speaker 1: Right.

Speaker 1: you give them, you can't do anything with them, you've got to throw them away because—

Speaker 2: you can't return a prescription medication.

Speaker 1: Yes, you could, especially with these ones because they're not, I forget the term, they're—

Speaker 2: not classified as something, controlled medication or something like that, they're not classified—

Speaker 1: as that.

Speaker 2: With your situation, if you're interested, Nick, I mean, you can keep those and I can—

Speaker 1: send you replacements if that's something that you're interested in, and I can make—

Speaker 2: sure that we send the AGV.

Speaker 1: No, I don't.

Speaker 2: Then they want me to send the pills back.

Speaker 1: Why should it be upon me to do it?

Speaker 2: I mean, if I have to call my bank and just reverse the charges, I will, but I'm trying—

Speaker 1: to avoid that.

Speaker 1: I mean, unfortunately, no.

Speaker 2: I mean, that's our policy, we do need the pills back.

Speaker 2: you that kick, okay?

Speaker 1: I can message the pharmacy right now and tell them to send you over 25 free pills to replace—

Speaker 2: the ones that you currently have.

Speaker 1: That way you have what you paid for, right?

Speaker 2: No, I'll just go the other route.

Speaker 1: I'll just call my bank and have them reverse the charges on the credit card.

Speaker 2: It's ridiculous, I didn't even finish out the order.

Speaker 1: I asked the girl, why'd they send me a refill?

Speaker 2: The doctor thought that you would probably want a refill, so they sent it to you.

Speaker 1: Really?

Speaker 2: Well, the prescription, when it gets written up, it does come with refills.

Speaker 1: I'd like to clarify that, okay?

Speaker 2: So, that's a standard practice for any medical industry, especially telehealth.

Speaker 1: The pills should be doing their thing, okay?

Speaker 2: I'm not sure if you've even tried the pills to begin with, but all of our pills are FDA—

Speaker 1: approved, so.

Speaker 2: I'm not fighting that point.

Speaker 1: I don't care if they're FDA approved or not.

Speaker 2: We were just messing around.

Speaker 1: We tried to try them, and then we said, no, we'll just cancel.

Speaker 2: Okay, so we canceled it.

Speaker 1: Just canceled it.

Speaker 2: Didn't even finish the order out.

Speaker 2: I thought, well, what the hell?

Speaker 1: I still have the pills.

Speaker 2: I'm not going to try to mess around with getting a refund from my bank.

Speaker 1: So, I just let it go.

Speaker 2: This time, I didn't ask for the refill.

Speaker 1: They sent the wrong pills to begin with.

Speaker 1: charges.

Speaker 2: I'm not asking for the first one.

Speaker 1: I have those pills, too.

Speaker 2: All I want you to do is be first or second to the refill that I never asked for.

Speaker 1: It's not that hard of a deal.

Speaker 2: Right.

Speaker 2: I need a minute, okay?

Speaker 2: I'm messaging people I need a message for this, so just give me a minute.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: All right, I got green light, Nick.

Speaker 2: I'm going to do that.

Speaker 1: I don't care about the first one.

Speaker 2: That was my mistake.

Speaker 1: I should have figured out a way to cancel better than what I did by just—

Speaker 2: closing the site down.

Speaker 1: I just want some refund on the $63.

Speaker 2: I just did right now, so you should be getting that within the next three to—

Speaker 1: five business days, not including the weekend, and that will be that, all—

Speaker 2: right?

Speaker 1: Yeah.

Speaker 2: I mean, do you see my point where they sent the wrong pills anyway?

Speaker 1: Look, I hear you already.

Speaker 2: I already heard that.

Speaker 1: I mean, no disrespect, but I already said I can replace every single pill—

Speaker 2: but we've already taken it this far.

Speaker 1: I've refunded everything.

Speaker 2: That's as far as I can go.

Speaker 1: We can send you confirmation of the refund.

Speaker 2: I hope you have a great rest of your day, okay, Nick?

Speaker 1: Where are you located at?

Speaker 2: Los Angeles, California.

Speaker 1: You're not getting the snow and stuff on the east side?

Speaker 2: No, not at all.

Speaker 1: It's nice and sunny right now, actually, and a little chilly, but nothing too—

Speaker 2: crazy.

Speaker 1: We live in Iowa, and we didn't get any snow.

Speaker 2: We don't have any cold weather.

Speaker 1: Yeah.

Speaker 2: I'm sure the rain season is coming pretty soon, though, so make sure you—

Speaker 1: guys stay dry, all right?

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: Thank you for your time.

Speaker 2: Send me an e-mail.

Speaker 1: Yeah, I'll send one.

Speaker 1: Thank you.

Speaker 1: Yep, take care.
